Text as data!?

Bennett Kleinberg

23 Feb 2021

research today

  • fundamentals of using (online) text data to study behaviour/cognition
  • text anonymisation
  • offline-online behaviour

why is text special?


  1. Its everywhere. And everything.
  2. Its really hard to make sense of.

Text as data


People need to follow the advice given properly, this is a very serious matter. Those self-centred people that arent doing so are endangering others lives, its infuriating!

text \(\neq\) data

  • Phase 1: text > behaviour/emotion/cognition
    • quantification issue
    • young discipline
  • Phase 2: text as a proxy for behaviour/emotion/cognition
    • pipeline into humans minds (Boyd & Schwartz, 2020)
  • Phase 3: large-scale studies on online behaviour
    • behaviour/emotion/cognition A > behaviour/emotion/cognition B
    • one or both operationalised through text data

We are in Phase 3 but havent paid attention to Phase 1

Promise and chaos

promise

  • text as data as a new lens on human behaviour and cognition
  • text as a proxy + computational methods
  • cheap and massive data (found data)
  • scale and granularity
  • coincides with major leaps in technical NLP (e.g., Word2Vec, GPT-3, BERT)

Rides on the computational social science wave (Lazer et al., 2009, Science)

knowingly ignored

  • No consensus, sampling issues, simplification (Tufekci, 2014, ICWSM)
  • Data quality problematic, willful ignorance about sampling (Morstatter et al., 2013, ICWSM)
  • Noncomparability, multiple comparisons problems, over-fitting (Ruths & Pfeffer, 2014, Science)

Missed opportunities:

Computational social science: Obstacles and opportunities (Lazer et al., 2020, Science)

dilemma

Anything goes & we get away with methodological murder

  • (Almost) everybody does it
  • Text data work sells (in research and outside)
  • Harder to do it well than to sell
  • We know where this might end

But we can save us all the trouble

but we know all this!

  • at the core lies a well-known problem
  • this is the measurement problem in a different coat!
  • concerns basic questions of psychometrics

If we want text as data to succeed, we need to go back to the fundamentals

Recent studies

emotion detection from text data

  • common practice: crowd-sourced annotation
  • relies on found data
  • results in large annotated corpora

But: it has an Achilles heel

test model

study 1: annotation error

  • data from the COVID-19 Real World Worry Dataset
  • participants were asked how they felt about the pandemic
  • and wrote two texts that expressed their current feelings

RQ: does the assumption of \(E' \approx E\) hold?

example (long)

I want to go back to how things were before. Im struggling to find the motivation to do things because were on lockdown, even though I have lots of university work to be doing. [] I am very grateful that I have my family, food and a place to stay. I am also grateful towards the NHS and all the key workers. Even though Im struggling with being inside the house all the time and missing my friends and family a lot, I know I am very lucky to be in the position I am in now. []

example (tweet)

Struggling with being inside the house all the time and feeling quite anxious. Grateful to have my family with me and thankful for the NHS

dataset

  • 2,500 long texts (avg. length: 127 words)
  • 2,500 Tweet-sized texts (avg. length: 28 words)
  • plus self-reported emotions

Annotator agreement and judgment precision:

Emotion [prev.] Kappa (short) Precision (short) Kappa (long) Precision (long)
Anxiety [0.55] 0.32 0.71 0.28 0.75
Fear [0.09] 0.21 0.16 0.22 0.21
Relaxation [0.13] 0.26 0.36 0.39 0.52
Sadness [0.14] 0.31 0.23 0.27 0.32
Average (all) 0.29 0.21 0.26 0.27
Average (Top 4) 0.28 0.37 0.29 0.45

near miss correction

Findings after adding \(\pm\) 1 point tolerance:

Emotion RWWD short RWWD long
Anxiety 0.94 (+0.23) 0.93 (+0.18)
Fear 0.51 (+0.35) 0.54 (+0.33)
Relaxation 0.57 (+0.21) 0.70 (+0.18)
Sadness 0.51 (+0.28) 0.60 (+0.28)
Average (all) 0.38 (+0.27) 0.50 (+0.23)
Average (Top 4) 0.63 (+0.26) 0.69 (+0.24)

findings

  • poor agreement
  • poor precision
  • best case scenario: annotation error of 0.37 (short) and 0.31 (long)
  • average: 0.63 (short) and 0.55 (long)
  • longer texts more useful than tweet-sized text
  • likely an underestimation of the annotation error

study 2: emotion induction

  • we are interested in writer emotions
  • so we need to work with that
  • preferred over annotation: self-reported emotions
  • even better: induced emotions

Lab-based methods not super useful for data-hungry models

experimental mood induction

  • participants saw a brief movie; either
    • a happy fragment from the Lion King
    • a sad fragment from the Lion King
    • a fragment from a documentary over magnets
    • Adapted from Marcusson-Clavertz et al.(2019)
  • then reported their emotions
  • and wrote a text

making people happy and sad

replication of annotation error

findings

  • optimistic about online emotion induction
  • replicated in another study + anger induction
  • annotation problem remains

Future work:

  • ground truth emotion corpus
  • other experimental elicitation of states: e.g.abusiveness

so what?

This can help us get the fundamentals right:

An outlook

2 problems

  1. Untested assumptions
  2. Too much freedom

Being boring to become sexy (again)

untested assumptions

  • we know very little about the cognition to language nexus
  • existing approaches not or poorly validated
  • a problem that is fully ignored

Way forward:

  • embracing experimental methods for ground truth dataset construction
  • acknowledging the assumptions
  • re-testing the idea of verbal behaviour longitudinally

too much freedom 1

Degrees of freedom in analysis + preprocessing

  • orders of magnitude bigger than in psychological research (text \(\neq\) numerical data)
  • adds a whole new layer
  • not present in current research

Way forward:

  • teaching old dogs new tricks: preregistration

too much freedom 2

Operationalisation diversity

  • frenzy of operationalisations
  • example: polarisation
  • consensus is lacking (or relying on non-validated tools)

Way forward:

  • proper validation studies (with known ground truth)
  • maturation over time

hope

  • some funders and practitioners become aware of the problems
  • the research community is active and alive
  • brilliant new PhD researchers and students

For every social scientist who rolls their eyes at yet another computer scientist butchering basic theories of human behavior, there is a computer scientist wincing in pain at yet another psychologist excitedly proclaiming that big data and machine learning solved their research problems with unbelievable accuracy. (Boyd & Schwartz, 2020, JLSP)
